[2]
Date: Fri, 19 Aug 2005
From: John Marr <jsmarr4@earthlink.com>
Source: NY Times [edited]
<http://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/19/nyregion/19sick.html>

A play area filled with water jets and sprinklers at a state park in
central New York has been identified as the source of a severe intestinal
illness that has stricken nearly 750 people in 3 weeks, the State Health
Department said yesterday.
Nearly all of the confirmed cases of the disease, a highly contagious
waterborne infection called cryptosporidiosis, have so far been traced to
the attraction, known as the Sprayground, at Seneca Lake State Park in
Geneva, N.Y., a Health Department spokesman, Jeffrey W. Hammond, said.
Although none of the people who were infected are known to be critically
ill, the outbreak may be among the largest ever involving cryptosporidiosis
in New York State, which typically has fewer than 500 cases a year.
The Sprayground, which gets about 43 000 visitors every August, was closed
on Monday after health officials noted more than 100 cases of the disease
in 8 counties. Last night, health officials said tests on a water tank that
feeds the play area had tested positive for cryptosporidiosis. The tank,
which uses water supplied by the nearby town of Waterloo, is used solely
for the Sprayground and has a chlorination and a filtration system.
A spokeswoman for the New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and
Historic Preservation, Wendy Gibson, said she thought the tank was the only
source of contaminated water, and said that a beach in the park would
remain open.
Health officials said, however, that they had not determined the extent of
the contamination and that they planned to run tests on drinking fountains
and other areas of the park. "Our investigation is ongoing, but so far we
know that that there was crypto in that tank," Mr. Hammond said.
The disease, which emerged in the United States in the 1970's, is known to
be one of the most frequent causes of traveler's diarrhea. Experts say it
is contracted primarily through contaminated food and tainted water
supplies and spreads very easily. Once it is picked up, the parasite lodges
itself in the victim's intestines for days or weeks, producing eggs and
causing severe abdominal pain, vomiting and diarrhea.
Outbreaks of the disease are fairly common. One of the worst, in Milwaukee
in 1993, sickened 400 000 people and killed a half-dozen. But generally the
disease is not deadly and lasts only about a week in most people, then goes
away on its own.
Last night, health officials advised those who had recently visited the
Sprayground and then experienced stomach problems to see a doctor. They
stressed that people who suspect they have contracted the disease should
wash their hands frequently and stay away from others; many cases reported
so far have occurred in groups, often among people in the same household.
The first cases in the 8 counties near Seneca Lake emerged in early July,
officials said. After an investigation, they found that most of the victims
were children who had played in the Sprayground and complained of nausea
and diarrhea a short time later. "We closed the Sprayground down
immediately, and it's now going to be closed for the season," Ms. Gibson said.
The largest number of cases, 309 as of last night, was in Ontario County,
and the bulk of all the cases, 746 as of last night, were confirmed this
week after the public was alerted to the outbreak. In Tompkins County, 25
cases were reported Tuesday and Wednesday -- compared with 2-3 in an
average year.
Ms. Gibson said the extent of the outbreak might have to do with the
popularity of the Sprayground, which is about 11 000 square feet and often
used by parents as well as children.
"It's accessible for different ages," Ms. Gibson said. "The beauty of it is
that it is pretty accessible for people and doesn't involve a pool. It's a
whole series of sprinklers."
[Byline: Anahad O'Connor, NY Times]
