[3]
Date: 19 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: WSTM.com
<http://www.wstm.com/Global/story.asp?s=3742696>

Number stricken by water park illness tops 1700
----------------------
The number of people who've reported getting sick after visiting an upstate
New York water playground has risen to more than 1700.
That's according to officials at the state Department of Health in Albany.
The agency says 1738 cases of illness have been reported in 20 counties.
Officials have traced the illness to the presence of cryptosporidium in 2
storage tanks that supply water to the popular "sprayground" at a park just
outside Geneva.
Known as crypto, the illness causes diarrhea, cramps, nausea, vomiting and
headache.
So far, health officials have confirmed 13 cases among those who have
reported getting ill after visiting the park.
The state has shut down the sprayground for the rest of the season.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[ProMED-mail would like to thank Lois Levitan <lcl3@cornell.edu> for
submitting an article with similar material on this outbreak. - Mod.MPP]
[Such parks distribute water as an aerosol, which apparently is a very
effective way of disseminating cryptosporidia. We are not aware of previous
outbreaks caused by such water parks, and it is clearly an exposure which
should be included in investigations of future outbreaks. The reports
mention that the water tank used as reservoir was chlorinated, but
cryptosporidia are relatively resistant to chlorination, and the treatment
was clearly not effective. - Mod.EP]
